"# Project Overview\nA lightweight, single-user todo-list web application (SPA) for personal use. The app provides a minimal, focused feature set: create, read, update, delete (CRUD) tasks and organize them via lists/projects. No user authentication or server components are required: data is stored locally in the browser. The product is intended to be simple, fast to load, and easy to maintain.\n\nKey goals\n- Minimal surface area: only features necessary for a personal todo app.\n- Local-only persistence (no cloud sync, no accounts).\n- Small, maintainable codebase suitable for quick implementation and static hosting.\n\n# Target Users\n- Individual users wanting a simple, personal task list accessible from a web browser.\n- No multi-user/team collaboration features, no shared data.\n\n# Functional Requirements\nCore functionality (MVP)\n1. Task CRUD\n   - Create a task with at least a title.\n   - Read/list tasks.\n   - Update task fields.\n   - Delete tasks.\n2. Lists / Projects\n   - Create, rename, delete lists/projects that group tasks.\n   - Assign a task to one list/project (a task belongs to zero or one project).\n3. Task model fields\n   - title (required)\n   - notes / description (optional)\n   - completed (boolean)\n   - dueDate (optional)\n   - projectId (nullable)\n   - createdAt / updatedAt (timestamps)\n4. Basic filtering and sorting\n   - Filter by list/project and completion status (all, active, completed).\n   - Sort by createdAt, dueDate, or custom order within a list (optional).\n5. Persistence\n   - Data persists across page reloads and browser restarts.\n6. UI\n   - Responsive layout for desktop and tablet. Mobile-friendly layout acceptable but not required to be optimized for small phones.\n   - Basic accessibility: keyboard focus on primary controls, semantic HTML.\n7. No authentication\n   - Users are anonymous; no sign-in or accounts.\n8. No external notifications / integrations at launch.\n\nExcluded from MVP\n- Syncing across devices.\n- Real-time collaboration.\n- Reminders, push notifications, attachments, comments, recurring tasks.\n- Third-party integrations (calendar, email, OAuth).\n\n# Non-functional Requirements\n- Performance: initial load time ≤ 1.5s on a typical broadband connection; interactions (create/update/delete) should respond instantly (UI updates immediately).\n- Availability: local-only; availability depends on the browser/device.\n- Offline behavior: because data is stored locally, the app works offline (no server component).\n- Scalability: designed for single-user local datasets—assume ≤ 5k tasks.\n- Size: keep production bundle < 1 MB if possible.\n- Accessibility: follow basic WCAG AA-ish patterns for keyboard navigation and focus management for primary interactions.\n- Maintainability: codebase in TypeScript, modular components, and a small set of dependencies.\n\n# Recommended Technology Stack\nFrontend\n- Framework: React (>=17) with TypeScript\n- Bundler / Dev server: Vite\n- State management: React context or a lightweight state library (Zustand) — given scope, React context + local data layer is sufficient.\n- Styling: CSS modules or Tailwind CSS (optional). Keep styling minimal.\n- IndexedDB helper: idb (small wrapper) or a tiny abstraction to simplify operations.\n- Testing: Jest + React Testing Library for unit tests; Cypress or Playwright for a minimal E2E test.\n\nBuild & Deploy\n- Static hosting: GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel\n- CI: GitHub Actions for build + test + deploy\n\nRationale: React + Vite + TypeScript is a minimal, widely-known stack with excellent DX and static-build deployment. IndexedDB is the recommended browser storage for structured data and larger datasets; fallback to localStorage for very small data or initial implementation is acceptable.\n\n# System Architecture\nHigh-level: Client-only Single Page Application (SPA) that persists data in the browser (IndexedDB). No backend or external APIs at launch.\n\nComponents\n- UI Layer\n  - Pages/Views: Task List View, Task Detail/Edit modal/drawer, Project/List Manager, Settings (minimal).\n  - Components: TaskItem, TaskEditor, ProjectList, Header, Footer.\n- Data Layer (client-side)\n  - Storage adapter (IndexedDB wrapper): handles all reads/writes and exposes a Promise-based API.\n  - TaskService: application-level functions (createTask, updateTask, deleteTask, listTasks, listTasksByProject).\n  - ProjectService: createProject, updateProject, deleteProject, listProjects.\n- State & Routing\n  - Local component state + context for global app state (current project filter, UI preferences).\n  - Client-side routing (optional) for direct links to a project or task.\n\nData flow\n- UI dispatches actions to TaskService → Storage adapter writes to IndexedDB → Storage adapter resolves Promise → UI updates state (optimistic update to maintain snappy UX).\n\nOffline & Persistence\n- Because storage is local, the app is available offline by default. No sync logic is required.\n\nSecurity perimeter\n- All data stays on the device. No network activity except retrieving static assets from hosting provider.\n\n# Database Requirements\nStorage: Browser-side IndexedDB (preferred) with idb wrapper. Provide fallback to localStorage for small datasets or browsers without IndexedDB support.\n\nSchema (object stores and indexes)\n- DB name: todo-app\n- Version: 1\n- Object stores:\n  1. projects\n     - keyPath: id (UUID string)\n     - fields:\n       - id: string (UUID)\n       - name: string\n       - createdAt: ISO timestamp\n       - updatedAt: ISO timestamp\n     - index: name (optional)\n  2. tasks\n     - keyPath: id (UUID string)\n     - fields:\n       - id: string (UUID)\n       - title: string\n       - description?: string\n       - completed: boolean (default false)\n       - dueDate?: ISO timestamp | null\n       - projectId?: string | null\n       - position?: number (for manual ordering within a project)\n       - createdAt: ISO timestamp\n       - updatedAt: ISO timestamp\n     - indexes:\n       - projectId (for listing tasks by project)\n       - completed (for filtering)\n       - dueDate (for sorting)\nNotes\n- Use UUID v4 strings for id generation (client-side).\n- Keep updates atomic using IndexedDB transactions across object stores if future features require cross-store writes (for now simple single-store writes suffice).\n- Expect dataset size per user to be small (< 5k tasks) so IndexedDB performance is adequate.\n\n# External Integrations\n- None at launch.\n- Optional future integrations (do not include in MVP): cloud sync, OAuth, push notifications, calendar sync.\n\n# Security Requirements\nGiven local-only storage and no authentication, security goals are small but important:\n1. Data locality\n   - All user data remains on the client device; do not transmit task data to third-party servers.\n2. Input sanitization\n   - Sanitize user-provided HTML when rendering rich text (if supporting anything beyond plain text). For MVP, treat descriptions as plain text; escape before rendering to prevent XSS.\n3. Secure dependencies\n   - Use minimal dependencies and audit them (npm audit or CI checks).\n4. Transport security\n   - Serve the app via HTTPS from static host to avoid man-in-the-middle of static assets.\n5. Browser protections\n   - Respect Content Security Policy (CSP) headers from hosting if supported to mitigate injection risks.\n6. No secrets stored\n   - No credential or token storage in the app.\n\n# API Requirements\nBecause the app is client-only, there is no HTTP API. Define a well-specified client-side module API (Storage/Service) that other modules/components will use. Below are function-level contracts (signatures described, not implementation).\n\nTaskService (Promise-based)\n- createTask(payload: { title: string; description?: string; dueDate?: string | null; projectId?: string | null; position?: number }): Promise<Task>\n- getTask(id: string): Promise<Task | null>\n- listTasks(filter?: { projectId?: string | null; completed?: boolean | 'all'; search?: string; sortBy?: 'createdAt' | 'dueDate' | 'position' }): Promise<Task[]>\n- updateTask(id: string, updates: Partial<TaskFields>): Promise<Task>\n- deleteTask(id: string): Promise<void>\n- toggleComplete(id: string): Promise<Task>\n\nProjectService\n- createProject(payload: { name: string }): Promise<Project>\n- getProject(id: string): Promise<Project | null>\n- listProjects(): Promise<Project[]>\n- updateProject(id: string, updates: Partial<ProjectFields>): Promise<Project>\n- deleteProject(id: string): Promise<void>\n\nStorage Adapter (IndexedDB abstraction)\n- openDB(): Promise<void>\n- get(store: 'tasks' | 'projects', key: string): Promise<any>\n- put(store: string, value: any): Promise<any>\n- delete(store: string, key: string): Promise<void>\n- getAll(store: string, query?: any, direction?: any): Promise<any[]>\n\nEvents / Observability\n- Provide a simple subscription mechanism for UI to be notified when storage changes (a simple EventEmitter or callback registration). Example: onTasksChanged(callback: () => void): Unsubscribe.\n\nError handling\n- Service functions should reject with meaningful errors. UI should display user-friendly messages for storage errors (rare).\n\n# Deployment\n- Build produces static assets (HTML/CSS/JS).\n- Recommended hosting: GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel.\n- CI: GitHub Actions workflow:\n  - Run lint, run unit tests, build.\n  - On merge to main, run deploy (upload to host).\n- Production environment:\n  - Serve over HTTPS.\n  - Configure caching headers for static assets; ensure index.html is served with short cache TTL if deployments change frequently, assets with content-hash can be long-lived.\n- Environment config: none required for runtime since no backend. Build-time variables: app name, version.\n\n# Testing Strategy\nUnit tests\n- Tools: Jest + React Testing Library.\n- Coverage:\n  - TaskService and ProjectService behavior (CRUD operations against an in-memory or mock idb).\n  - Storage adapter tests (integration tests with IndexedDB shim like fake-indexeddb for Node).\n  - UI components: TaskItem, TaskEditor — interactions and state updates.\n\nE2E tests\n- Tools: Cypress or Playwright.\n- Scenarios:\n  - Create a new task, edit it, mark complete, delete it; verify persistence after reload.\n  - Create a project, assign tasks to it, filter by project.\n  - UI accessibility checks: keyboard navigation for adding and completing tasks.\n\nManual QA\n- Cross-browser smoke tests on latest Chrome, Firefox, and Safari.\n- Mobile/Tablet responsiveness verification.\n\nQuality gates in CI\n- Linting must pass.\n- Unit tests must pass; aim for a minimal coverage target (e.g., 60–70%) for core modules.\n- E2E test suite run on merge to main before deployment.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\nThe product is acceptable when the following are met:\n1. Task CRUD\n   - User can create a task with a title, view it in the list, edit any field, and delete it.\n2. Project management\n   - User can create, rename, and delete projects; tasks can be assigned to projects.\n3. Persistence\n   - Created tasks and projects persist after page reload and browser restart using browser storage.\n4. Filtering & Sorting\n   - User can filter tasks by project and by completion state and can sort by createdAt or dueDate.\n5. Responsiveness & Accessibility\n   - UI is responsive on desktop/tablet; primary actions accessible by keyboard.\n6. No external network dependencies for data\n   - App functions fully without network access for data operations (static assets may require network).\n7. Tests & CI\n   - Unit tests and CI pipelines configured and passing for the repository.\n8. Documentation\n   - README includes setup/build/deploy/test instructions.\n\n# Deliverables\n1. Source code repository with:\n   - TypeScript React SPA code.\n   - Storage adapter for IndexedDB (and fallback to localStorage).\n   - TaskService and ProjectService modules.\n   - UI components for task list, task editor, project manager.\n   - Basic styling and responsive layout.\n2. Tests\n   - Unit tests covering services and core components.\n   - Minimal E2E test suite for primary user flows.\n3. CI configuration\n   - GitHub Actions workflow for build/test/deploy.\n4. Deployment config\n   - Scripts and instructions for deploying to GitHub Pages / Netlify / Vercel.\n5. Documentation\n   - README with app overview, dev setup, build, test, and deploy steps.\n   - Simple API documentation for the client-side services (function signatures and expected inputs/outputs).\n6. Acceptance checklist (mapped to Acceptance Criteria) to verify the delivered app.\n\nAdditional notes / Implementation constraints\n- Keep third-party dependencies to a minimum.\n- Keep UI/UX simple and clear — avoid rich text editing or HTML in descriptions for MVP.\n- Where possible, implement optimistic UI updates for immediate responsiveness, with fallback/error handling if storage operations fail.\n- For IndexedDB interactions in unit tests, use fake-indexeddb to simulate browser environment.\n\nThis specification is intentionally minimal and focused on the user request: a simple, single-user web SPA todo app with local persistence and basic task/list CRUD. If you want server-backed persistence, multi-device sync, or user accounts later, a follow-up spec will be required to define server APIs, authentication flows, data migration, and sync/conflict resolution."